{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.07,0.05,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28766"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44905"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset central chest pain and syncope. The chest pain started one hour ago and radiates to her back. The pain is constant, severe and 9/10 in intensity. She has a medical history of hypertension. Her medications include amlodipine. Social history reveals that she has been an active cocaine user for the past five years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she looks unwell and in pain. The blood pressure in the left arm is 125/85 mmHg and on the right arm it is 145/85 mmHg. On auscultation there is a diastolic murmur heard best on the left second intercostal space. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT angiography","Chest X-ray","Troponin level","CT pulmonary angiography","Chest ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eaortic dissection. Acute aortic dissection (AAD) occurs when there is a tear on the intima layer of the aorta, creating a false lumen that allows blood to flow between the intima and the media wall. Aortic dissection can be classified using the Stanford system or the DeBakey classification. The Stanford system classified AAD according to the location of the tear in accordance to the ascending aorta. Stanford A indicates that the ascending aorta is affected, while Stanford B indicates that there is sparing of the ascending aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAAD is associated with high mortality and morbidity due to aortic rupture and coronary dissection. Prompt diagnosis and management is important to improve the patient\u0027s prognosis. Risk factors of developing aortic dissection include hypertension, cocaine use, and marfan syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAAD commonly present as an acute severe chest pain that radiates to the back. It is also associated with neurological deficit including paraesthesia and altered mental status. The gold standard investigation for AAD is a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E that allows clinician to visualise the dissection. Other mode of investigation that is commonly used is the transthoracic echocardiogram. Urgent cardiothoracic referral needs to be done for all patients with suspected aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate tool to diagnose aortic dissection as the result might be inconclusive and non-specific. Several findings of AAD include mediastinal widening and abnormal aortic contour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETroponin level \u003C/strong\u003Eis needed to rule out myocardial infarction, which is an important differential in this case. However due to the ECG findings, myocardial infarction is much less likely therefore it is not the most appropriate diagnostic test for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for pulmonary embolism which is a less likely diagnosis in this scenario. Patients with pulmonary embolism usually present with sharp chest pain accompanied by shortness of breath or a cough. Central chest pain radiating to the back is also uncommon symptoms of pulmonary embolism. Furthermore the patient does not have any risk factors for hypercoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a common investigation for acute aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Risk factors of aortic dissection are hypertension, cocaine use, and marfan syndrome.","Aortic dissection present with severe chest pain radiating to the back."],"references":["Carrel T, Sundt TM. von Kodolitsch Y. Acute aortic dissection Lancet. 2023; 401:773-88."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28766"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28766"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-27T08:54:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-27T08:54:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43777"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"